    "mbti.history.origins.title": "1. Origins – Carl Jung",
    "mbti.history.origins.desc": "In 1921, Swiss psychiatrist <strong>Carl Gustav Jung</strong> published <em>Psychological Types</em>, in which he developed a theory of psychological functions: sensation, intuition, thinking, and feeling. He proposed that each person favors a dominant function, which can be introverted or extraverted.",
    "mbti.history.katharine.title": "2. Katharine Cook Briggs – First steps",
    "mbti.history.katharine.desc1": "From 1917, <strong>Katharine Cook Briggs</strong> became fascinated by personality differences after noticing the distinctive profile of her future son-in-law. She began reading biographies, developing an initial typology of four temperaments: contemplative, spontaneous, executive, social.",
    "mbti.history.katharine.desc2": "After <em>Psychological Types</em> was translated into English (1923), she linked her temperaments to Jung's typology. She published articles in 1926 and 1928 (\"Meet Yourself Using the Personality Paint Box\", \"Up From Barbarism\") to promote the theory.",
    "mbti.history.isabel.title": "3. Isabel Briggs Myers – Formalization during World War II",
    "mbti.history.isabel.desc1": "<strong>Isabel Briggs Myers</strong>, Katharine's daughter and a political science graduate, learned statistical methods and psychometric testing from Edward N. Hay.",
    "mbti.history.isabel.desc2": "During World War II, mother and daughter developed a psychological tool to help women find jobs suited to their personality. In 1943 they self-published the <em>Briggs Myers Type Indicator Handbook</em>, and in 1956 it was officially republished as the MBTI.",
    "mbti.history.diffusion.title": "4. Spread and development",
    "mbti.history.diffusion.desc1": "In 1962, the <em>Educational Testing Service</em> (ETS) published the first manual version of the MBTI. It received support from academics such as Donald MacKinnon and Mary McCaulley. Publication was transferred to <em>Consulting Psychologists Press</em> in 1975, which became The Myers-Briggs Company, with the Center for Applications of Psychological Type (CAPT) as a research center.",
    "mbti.history.diffusion.desc2": "After Isabel's death in 1980, Mary McCaulley published the second edition of the manual in 1985, then a third in 1998.",
    "mbti.history.diffusion.desc3": "The test has been regularly revised (Form M, Form Q) using modern methods such as <em>item response theory</em> (IRT) to improve technical accuracy.",
    "mbti.history.popularity.title": "5. Popularity… and controversies",
    "mbti.history.popularity.desc1": "Today the MBTI is one of the most widely used personality tests: more than <strong>2 million people</strong> take it each year, and it is commonly used in businesses, universities, career counseling and even the military.",
    "mbti.history.popularity.desc2": "But scientifically, it is often criticized:",
    "mbti.history.popularity.list1": "Lack of reliability (retest: 50% of types can change within a few weeks)",
    "mbti.history.popularity.list2": "Low psychometric validity, absence of continuous trait measurement",
    "mbti.history.popularity.list3": "Barnum effect (descriptions too vague)",
    "mbti.history.popularity.list4": "Considered pseudo-scientific by the academic community",
    "mbti.history.influence.title": "6. Derived influence – Keirsey, the temperaments",
    "mbti.history.influence.desc": "<strong>David Keirsey</strong> drew on the MBTI to propose a model of four temperaments (Guardian, Artisan, Idealist, Rational) corresponding to MBTI axes (SJ, SP, NF, NT). His system <em>Please Understand Me</em> widely popularized these types.",
